2. `>[-]`: Move the data pointer to the right again and set the cell to 0.
3. `<>`: Move the data pointer left and then right, effectively staying in the same position.
4. `++++++++++`: Increment the current cell (cell 2) by 10.
5. `[<++++++++++>-]`: This loop will run 10 times, decrementing the current cell (cell 2) each time and incrementing the previous cell (cell 1) by 10. After the loop, cell 2 will be 0, and cell 1 will be 100.

8. `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value in cell 1, which is 97 ('a').

10. `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value in cell 1, which is 108 ('l').
11. `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value in cell 1 again, which is 108 ('l').
12. `+++++++++++++`: Increment the current cell (cell 1) by 13, making it 121.
13. `.`: Output the character corresponding to the ASCII value in cell 1, which is 121 ('y').
